What is the structure of the dataset?¶

There are 183,412 records in the dataset with 16 features. Using the bike_id variable, there are 4646 bikes in the dataset. Most variables are numeric in nature, some are nominal data(user_type, member_gender and bike_share_for_all_trip), while others are datetime

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

when are most trips taken/started in terms of time of day, day of week, month of the year
What are the number of rdies taken per gender
How long does the average trip take
Does the length of the trip depend on the user being a customer of subscriber

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The variable that will be most helpful in this analysis are duration_sec, start_time and end_time, user_type and member_gender

Adding Columns¶

In [8]:
# Splitting the start_time column into the variables to form separate columns

bike_new['start_hour'] = pd.to_datetime(bike_new['start_time']).dt.hour
bike_new['start_day'] = pd.to_datetime(bike_new['start_time']).dt.strftime('%a')
bike_new['start_month'] = pd.to_datetime(bike_new['start_time']).dt.strftime('%b')
In [9]:
# mapping the hour column inorder to convert it from 24 hour to 12 hour time format

bike_new['start_hour'] = bike_new['start_hour'].map({0:'12AM',1:'1AM', 2:'2AM', 3:'3AM', 4:'4AM', 5:'5AM', 6:'6AM', 7:'7AM',
                                                     8:'8AM', 9:'9AM', 10:'10AM', 11:'11AM', 12: '12PM', 13:'1PM', 
                                                     14: '2PM', 15:'3PM', 16: '4PM', 17:'5PM', 18: '6PM', 19:'7PM', 
                                                     20: '8PM', 21:'9PM', 22: '10PM', 23:'11PM'})
In [10]:
hour_format = ['12AM', '1AM', '2AM', '3AM', '4AM', '5AM', '6AM', '7AM', '8AM', '9AM', '10AM', '11AM', '12PM', '1PM', 
               '2PM', '3PM', '4PM', '5PM', '6PM', '7PM', '8PM', '9PM', '10PM', '11PM',]

# Returns the start_hour with the categories and orderedness
start_hour_order = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=hour_format)

bike_new['start_hour'] = bike_new['start_hour'].astype(start_hour_order)
In [11]:
# Ordering start_day column according to the order of the days of the week
day_format = ['Mon', 'Tue', 'Wed', 'Thu', 'Fri', 'Sat', 'Sun']

# Returns the day_format with the categories and orderedness
day_format_order = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=day_format)

bike_new['start_day'] = bike_new['start_day'].astype(day_format_order)
In [12]:
#Coverting the time spent riding the bike from sec to minutes
bike_new['duration_min'] = bike_new['duration_sec'].apply(lambda x: x/60).round(2)

# Using this year (2022) i subtracted the birth year from 2022 to get the age of the bike drivers 
bike_new['member_age'] = bike_new['member_birth_year'].apply(lambda x: 2022 - x)

Univariate Exploration¶

I'll start by looking at the distribution of the main variable of interest: Trips taken per day, hour, month and gender.

Question: Number and proportion of rides taken per day¶
In [18]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10.5,6))

ax = sns.countplot(x =bike_new['start_day'], color='#da2216')
 
# code used to add label and proportion to the chart
abs_values = bike_new['start_day'].value_counts()
rel_values = bike_new['start_day'].value_counts(normalize=True).values * 100
lbls = [f'{p[0]} ({p[1]:.1f}%)' for p in zip(abs_values, rel_values)]

plt.ylabel('Number of Rides')
plt.xlabel('Day');
plt.title('THE NUMBER AND PROPORTION OF RIDES TAKEN PER DAY')
ax.bar_label(container=ax.containers[0], labels=lbls);

The chart shows more people take bike rides during the weekday than on weekends with Thursday having the highest number of rides taken with 35197 rides and 19.2% share of the total rides taken. This was closely followed by Tuesday (31813, 17.3%), Wednesday (29641, 16.2%), Friday (28981, 15.8%), Monday (16852, 14.6%), Sunday (15523, 8.5%) and saturday (15405, 8.4%).

The difference in ratio between other days compared with saturday and sunday shows that more people should be encouraged to participate more on those days.

The periods with the lowest participation are in the early hours of the morning between (12AM - 5AM). The periods of peak participation (top 5) with the highest number of riding activities are 5PM with 21,864 rides which is 11.92% of the total rides. Others are: 8AM (21056, 11.48%), 6PM (16827, 9.17%), 9AM (15903, 8.67%) and 4PM (14169, 7.73%)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  • Most rides were taken on thursday and the time with the highest rides taken was 5pm
  • The age variable took on a large range of values, so I looked at the data using a log transform. Under the transformation, the data looked unimodal, with the peak between 30 - 35 years.
  • I used log scale for the duration (minutes) variable and the data looked unimodal, with peak the between 10 - 12 minutes

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • When investigating the dataset, i created a day, time, and month variables from the start_time variable and mapped the time variable from 24hrs to 12hrs time format. Also, i converted the duration from seconds to minutes
  • Created an age variable by substracting the birth year from 2022 which was the year this analysis was carried out
  • i dropped the columns: duration_sec', 'start_station_latitude', 'end_station_latitude', 'start_station_longitude', 'end_station_longitude', 'start_station_id', 'end_station_id', 'member_birth_year'

def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    default_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
    sns.boxplot(x=x, y=y, color = default_color)

plt.figure(figsize = [9,9])
g = sns.PairGrid(data = bike_subset, y_vars = ['member_age'], x_vars = x_vars,
                height = 4, aspect = 1.3)
g.map(boxgrid)

# I used personal ticks for the y-axis
ticks = [20,25,30,35,40,45,50,55,60,65,70,75,80]
labels = ['{}'.format(v) for v in ticks]
plt.yticks(ticks, labels);

plt.subplots_adjust(wspace= 0.2);

<Figure size 648x648 with 0 Axes>

i. user_type: The median values of riders that are customers is approximately 37 years, while that for subscribers is 35 years. This shows that the age of riders that are customers are on average higher than those that are subscribers. The top whisker been longer than the bottom shows the age of the members are more concentrated within a narrower range of values than in the top whisker. Also, the amount of outliers show that subscribers have a lot of older members.

ii. member_gender: The median values that are male is 35, for female it is 34 while for other it is 38. This shows that the age of riders that are male are on average higher than those for female. The plot also shows that all the genders have more riders around the lower end of the age distribution.

More males and other gender come out around 5pm, then 8am, while more females come out around 8am, then 5pm, after that, they share the same preference for the next top 4 hours of the day they come to bike ride, which are 6pm, 9am and 4pm, 7am
The hour with the least participation for males is 3am, for female it is 3am, while for other gender it is 5am

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

  • There is a weak relationship between the age of the ride and the time spend bike riding
  • Inteesting the larger the frequency of bike rides taken by gender or user type (customer/subscribers) the smaller the average value of the duration covered.
